data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new built-in span conversions cause **overload resolution to change**. `array.Contains(num)` on `int[]` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent `ReadOnlySpan<T>`** operations, so this fails at runtime when the interpreted expression tree tries to invoke the span-based method.

## Fix

Force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three ensure the `Enumerable.Contains` overload is selected, which is expression-tree compatible.
